malized": false, "mention": "bovine", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9316944479942322, "span": {"begin": 506, "end": 512}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rat", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9870391488075256, "span": {"begin": 542, "end": 545}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005978"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GSH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9965062141418457, "span": {"begin": 585, "end": 588}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000111"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "N-acetylcysteine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995856285095215, "span": {"begin": 619, "end": 635}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002635"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Chen et al", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8426971435546875, "span": {"begin": 637, "end": 647}}], "text": "When antioxidant defence&nbsp;mechanisms become overwhelmed by high local oxidant concentrations, GSSG can interact with protein thiol groups to form protein-GSSG adducts, a process termed S-glutathionylation&nbsp;(Schuppe et al. 1992).  Hypoxia/reoxygenation-induced oxidative stress (associated with ischaemia-reperfusion injury) was shown to deplete GSH in bovine aortic endothelial cells, which led to S-glutathionylation of eNOS and eNOS uncoupling.&nbsp; This phenomenon was partially reversible, in bovine aortic endothelial cells and rat aortic rings, by raising intracellular GSH levels upon administration of N-acetylcysteine (Chen et al. 2010, DePascali et al. 2014).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:53:36 +0000 2026"}